nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub24.ezboard.com/utwistofsin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>twistofsin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elvis? Who's Elvis?</span><br>  Posts: 74<br> <font color=#333333>(12/14/01 9:11:57 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub24.ezboard.com/fnonguildfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1170.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Bodin? Tech heads?</span><hr size=1> About the only thing that does, is help prevent fragmentation on your primary drive (which maintenance does anyway.) Or, if you wanna be a real stickler you could say that theoretically, your primary drive is accessed much less frequently because as a gamer, your swap file gives the HD tons more abuse then any storage actually does. Personally, I don't think it's worth it to have a few hundred extra megs when HD's are running from about $65 for20 gigs to only 220 for 120 gig IDE drives now.<br><br>This is something you do with a file or database server or anything else that is getting information sucked off the HD's constantly, because then the fragmentation does have a noticable effect over time. Not saying fragmentation does'nt affect your own computer, but the effects are'nt serious unless your data looks like a shattered window on your HD.<br><br>Oh, and watch what Windows does when you try to boot up and you have an illegal swap drive specificated and not tons of ram QQ~!<br><br><br>Nilbo. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub24.ezboard.com/ucrailtarget.showPublicProfile?language=EN>CRailTarget</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 74<br> <font color=#333333>(12/14/01 9:22:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub24.ezboard.com/fnonguildfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1170.topic&index=3>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Bodin? Tech heads?</span><hr size=1> Under Win95/98 there is a simple way to prevent swap fragmentation - just set its size manually, min and max size to the same amount, equal maybe to 2 times the size of physical memory, or 2 and a half, no point in more. Then defragment it once with a decent defragmentation software (not one included with Windows), and there you go. No fragmentation no more.<br><br>Aethor<br> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub24.ezboard.com/ucrailtarget.showPublicProfile?language=EN>CRailTarget</A> at: 12/14/01 9:23:05 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub24.ezboard.com/uyaxa.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Yaxa</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.remagination.net/yaxa/ynew.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mr. Wizard~la Pet~la Happy~la</span><br>  Posts: 445<br> <font color=#333333>(12/14/01 9:45:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub24.ezboard.com/fnonguildfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1170.topic&index=4>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.remagination.net/yaxa/yaxportrait.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Bodin? Tech heads?</span><hr size=1> Using a second hard disk for the swap file *does* increase the performance, but only if the HD is a 'good' one. I wouldn't recommend using an old (read: slow!) HD for the swap file. <p><CENTER> <BR><A HREF="http://eq.castersrealm.com/players/view_profile.asp?Id=65975"><IMG SRC="http://www.remagination.net/yaxa/yaxsig11.jpg" ALT="Yaxa Brightmoon" WIDTH="400" HEIGHT="100" BORDER="0"></A></CENTER></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub24.ezboard.com/udashaaonnameless.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dashaa on Nameless</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#333333>(12/15/01 12:31:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub24.ezboard.com/fnonguildfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1170.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_arrowdown.gif" align=absmiddle>  My Two Cents Worth </span><hr size=1> OK as for the swap file...How much RAM does the system have first of all?<br><br>Let's say you have 128MB RAM (It should work with only 64MB but be careful the system might not boot and you would have to go into Safe Mode) and Windows 98 or above.  Go to the Performance Tab, Virtual Memory, Let Me Specify ..., and Check Disable.<br><br>When this is done reboot your system.  Defrag the drive without the swap file and then set it back to Let Windows Manage ... within the Performance Tab and reboot.<br><br>You have just defraged your swap file.<br><br>Also Norton and Diskkeeper at www.executivesoftware.com are great programs for keeping things in line.<br><br>Four problems with adding another Harddrive:<br><br>1) Most compters have one faster IDE channel than the others (ATA100...etc).  I try to simplify things by placing the primary harddrive and CDROM on the same channel.  You can put the second harddrive on the fast channel but you need another cable to reattach the CDROM to another connection.<br><br>2) If the harddrives are different types/speeds it could degrade the overall performance.  Since most high performance Harddrives are 4GB and above this would be a waste of a good Harddrive.<br><br>3) Just another thing to break and cause problems.<br><br>4) HEAT !!! Most cases have the 3 1/2 bays in one cage.  So you would have two harddrives and a floppy all sandwiched together. Put the Harddrive and floppy drive apart for cooling.<br><br>This is what I get to do all day now <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>Dash <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub24.ezboard.com/unonhealer.showPublicProfile?language=EN>nonhealer</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.namelesslords.com/flag.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Super Spandex Man</span><br>  Posts: 3113<br> <font color=#333333>(12/17/01 7:47:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub24.ezboard.com/fnonguildfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1170.topic&index=6>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.namelesslords.com/sigfiles/bodin6060.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_arrowdown.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: My Two Cents Worth </span><hr size=1> And you all thought I was bad....<br><br>Dasha over there is listing the tolerance of teh bearings that spin withen a hard drive... <p><html><head><title></title></head><body><p align="center">Bodin Battlehealer | The Nameless Lords | Vicar of Ro